# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The **1882 Boston Red Caps season** was the 12th season of the franchise.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps were a team in transition, as co-founder and longtime manager Harry Wright left the team and was replaced by John Morrill.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1882 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 45–39 record, good for third place in the National League.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues finished the 1882 season at 42–40, fifth place in the National League.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1882 Detroit Wolverines** finished the season with a 42–41 record, good for fifth place in the National League.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] During the season, Detroit owner William G.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] Thompson had a private investigator look into umpire Richard Higham, after suspicions of matchfixing, which resulted in Higham becoming the only umpire to be banned in MLB history.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
